### |project://rascal/src/org/rascalmpl/library/Content.rsc|
[3m[2m@synopsis{Content provides access to the content server of the Rascal terminal for viewing interactive HTML output.}[0m
[1mmodule[0m Content

[1mimport[0m lang::json::IO;

[3m[2m@synopsis{Content wraps the HTTP Request/Response API to support interactive visualization types
on the terminal.}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
Values wrapped in a `Content` wrapper will be displayed by interactive
Rascal applications such as the IDE, the REPL terminal and the documentation pages. 

```rascal-prepare
import Content;
```

For example, a piece of html can be displayed directly like such:
```rascal-shell,continue
html("\<a href=\"http://www.rascal-mpl.org\"\>Rascal homepage\</a\>")
```

In its most general form, `Content` is an HTTP(s) webserver callback, such that you might deliver
any kind of content, based on any kind of request. If you produce a `Content` value
which processes requests dynamically, subsequent interaction from the web browser will be 
processed as well. So using the `Content` wrapper you can start an interactive user experience
in the browser directly from the REPL. 

Content values stay plugged into the application server that is hidden in the REPL 
environment until they have not been used for at least 30 minutes. If you want the same
interaction back after 30 minutes of non-usage, you have to produce another Content value 
on the commandline. 

When you are happy with the interaction, or you want a permanent visualization which is not
garbage collected after 30 minutes, you can consider wrapping the same callback in
a webserver using the ((util::Webserver::serve)) function.
}[0m
[1mdata[0m Content
    = content(
          [1mstr[0m id, Response(Request) callback,
          [1mstr[0m title = id,
          ViewColumn viewColumn = normalViewColumn(1))
    | content(
          Response response,
          [1mstr[0m title = "*static content*",
          ViewColumn viewColumn = normalViewColumn(1))
    ;

[3m[2m@synopsis{Directly serve a static html page}[0m
Content html([1mstr[0m html) = content(response(html));

[3m[2m@synopsis{Directly serve the contents of a file}[0m
Content file([1mloc[0m src) = content(response(src));

[3m[2m@synopsis{Directly serve the contents of a string as plain text}[0m
Content plainText([1mstr[0m text) = content(plain(text));

[1malias[0m Body = [1mvalue[0m([1mtype[0m[[1mvalue[0m] expected);

[3m[2m@synopsis{Request values represent what a browser is asking for, most importantly the URL path.}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
A request value also contains the full HTTP headers, the URL parameters as a `map[str,str]`
and possibly uploaded content, also coded as a map[str,str]. From the constructor type,
`put` or `get` you can see what kind of HTTP request it was.
}[0m
[3m[2m@pitfalls{
* Note that `put` and `post` have not been implemented yet in the REPL server.
}[0m
[1mdata[0m Request ([1mmap[0m[[1mstr[0m, [1mstr[0m] headers = (),
              [1mmap[0m[[1mstr[0m, [1mstr[0m] parameters = (),
              [1mmap[0m[[1mstr[0m, [1mstr[0m] uploads = ())
    = get([1mstr[0m path)
    | put([1mstr[0m path, Body content)
    | post([1mstr[0m path, Body content)
    | delete([1mstr[0m path)
    | head([1mstr[0m path)
    ;

[3m[2m@synopsis{A response encodes what is send back from the server to the browser client.}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
The three kinds of responses, encode either content that is already a `str`,
some file which is streamed directly from its source location or a jsonResponse
which involves a handy, automatic, encoding of Rascal values into json values.
}[0m
[1mdata[0m Response
    = response(Status status, [1mstr[0m mimeType, [1mmap[0m[[1mstr[0m, [1mstr[0m] header, [1mstr[0m content)
    | fileResponse([1mloc[0m file, [1mstr[0m mimeType, [1mmap[0m[[1mstr[0m, [1mstr[0m] header)
    | jsonResponse(
          Status status, [1mmap[0m[[1mstr[0m, [1mstr[0m] header, [1mvalue[0m val,
          [1mstr[0m dateTimeFormat = "yyyy-MM-dd\'T\'HH:mm:ss\'Z\'",
          JSONFormatter[[1mvalue[0m] formatter = [1mstr[0m ([1mvalue[0m _){ [1mfail[0m; },
          [1mbool[0m explicitConstructorNames = [1mfalse[0m,
          [1mbool[0m explicitDataTypes = [1mfalse[0m,
          [1mbool[0m dateTimeAsInt = [1mtrue[0m,
          [1mbool[0m rationalsAsString = [1mfalse[0m)
    ;

[3m[2m@synopsis{Utility to quickly render a string as HTML content}[0m
Response response([1mstr[0m content, [1mmap[0m[[1mstr[0m, [1mstr[0m] header = ())
