[3m[2m@synopsis{Register an M3 model for a certain project name.}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
The effect of registering a project is that the m3 URI resolver knows how to find the physical source location
for qualified names.

Note that ((registerProject)) will be called usually as a side-effect of a function that extracts a model for
a specific language.
}[0m
[3m[2m@benefits{
*  this enables qualified names as locations to be hyperlinks in the IDE
}[0m
[3m[2m@pitfalls{
*  the registry is a global store that will retain links to M3 models even when they are not in use anymore. The 
programmer should take care to call ((unregisterProject)) to prevent memory leakage.
}[0m
[1mvoid[0m registerProject([1mloc[0m project, M3 model) {
    [1mrel[0m[[1mstr[0m scheme, [1mloc[0m name, [1mloc[0m src] perScheme
        = {<name.scheme, name, src>| <name, src> <- model.declarations};
    
    [1mfor[0m ([1mstr[0m scheme <- perScheme<scheme>) {
        registerLocations(
            scheme, project.authority, (name: src| <name, src> <- perScheme[scheme])
        );
    }
}

[3m[2m@synopsis{unregister an M3 model for a certain project name.}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
The effect of unregistering a project is that all references will be
removed from the registry, clearing memory.
}[0m
[3m[2m@benefits{
*  this cleans up the memory used by the registry
}[0m
[3m[2m@pitfalls{
*  if a different model is used for unregistering than for registering,
   there could be a memory leak of remaining schemes and their respective locations.
}[0m
[1mvoid[0m unregisterProject([1mloc[0m project, M3 model) {
    [1mfor[0m ([1mloc[0m name <- model.declarations<name>) {
        unregisterLocations(name.scheme, project.authority);
    }
}

[3m[2m@synopsis{unregister an M3 model for a set of given schemes}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
The effect of unregistering a project is that all references will be
removed from the registry, clearing memory.
}[0m
[3m[2m@benefits{
* This cleans up the memory used by the registry, and by giving all possible
   schemes for a certain language the chance is high there are not dangling
   entries afterwards.
}[0m
[3m[2m@pitfalls{
*  If more schemes were registered than are unregistered here, there is a
   memory leak.
}[0m
[1mvoid[0m unregisterProjectSchemes([1mloc[0m project, [1mset[0m[[1mstr[0m] schemes) {
    [1mfor[0m ([1mstr[0m scheme <- schemes) {
        unregisterLocations(scheme, project.authority);
    }
}
### |project://rascal/src/org/rascalmpl/library/analysis/m3/TypeSymbol.rsc|
[3m[2m@synopsis{Symbolic representation for types that occur in programming languages.}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
M3 provides a general mechanism to associate types, symbolically, with source code artifacts or even run-time artifacts.

The `TypeSymbol` type is a general concept which needs to be extended for specific programming languages. One language will 
class and interface definitions which coincide with types, another may have higher order function types etc.

As a basic principle, the symbols for declared types always link to their definition in the source code using a location value, while other implicit types do not have such a link (i.e. `int` and `void`).

We cater for languages to have a subtype relation to be defined, and a least upper bound computation. 
}[0m
[3m[2m@benefits{
* symbolic types can be analyzed and manipulated symbolically, i.e. to instantiate parametrized types.
* symbolic types can be used directly as constraint variables for type inference or type-based refactoring purposes.
}[0m
[3m[2m@pitfalls{
* If you import extensions to this M3 model for two different languages, ambiguity and other confusion may arise 
because the subtype and lub functions of the two languages will merge.
* TypeSymbols are sometimes confused with their predecessors in the analysis pipeline: abstract syntax trees of `Type`.
   * If `Type` is the syntax of types, then `TypeSymbol` represents their semantics.
   * Programmers can only type in `Type` instances, while programming languages may also feature types which do not have syntax (such as union an intersection types during inference).
   * Type and TypeSymbol constructors are the same when they are related, i.e. Type::\int() will produce TypeSymbol::\int().
   * Often different ways of writing the same type in syntax, produce a normal and simplified form in TypeSymbol representation.
   * Abstract or generic (parameterized) TypeSymbols can be instantiated during abstract interpretation and other analysis algorithms.
   * Instances of syntactic `Type` always have their `src` location with them, while most TypeSymbols are deduced and inferred and do not
   have a clear source origin.
}[0m
[1mmodule[0m analysis::m3::TypeSymbol

[1mdata[0m TypeSymbol = unresolved();
