}[0m
[3m[2m@contributor{Jurgen J. Vinju - Jurgen.Vinju@cwi.nl - CWI}[0m
[3m[2m@contributor{Bert Lisser - Bert.Lisser@cwi.nl (CWI)}[0m
[3m[2m@synopsis{Two-dimensional text layout algorithm}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
The input to Box2Text is a hierarchy of "Boxes" represented by the ((lang::box::\syntax::Box)) algebraic data-type.
These boxes put hard and soft relative positioning constraints on the embedded text fragments, and
there is the global soft constraints of the width of the screen (or the paper). 


This implementation is a port from ASF+SDF to Rascal. The ASF+SDF implementation was published as 
"From Box to Tex:An algebraic approach to the construction of documentation tools" by Mark van den Brand 
and Eelco Visser (June 30, 1994). The original Box concept was introduced by Joel Coutaz as this technical report:
"The Box, A Layout Abstraction for User Interface Toolkits" (1984) Pittsburgh, PA: Carnegie Mellon University.

The main function `format` maps a Box tree to a `str`:
* To obtain Box terms people typically transform ASTs or ((ParseTree))s to Box using pattern matching in Rascal.
* ((Options)) encode global default options for constraint parameters that only override local parameters if they were elided.
}[0m
[3m[2m@examples{
This demonstrates the semantics of the main hard constraints:
* `H` for horizontal;
* `V` for vertical;
* `I` for indentation.

```rascal-shell
import lang::box::util::Box2Text;
import lang::box::\syntax::Box;
format(H(L("A"), L("B"), L("C"), hs=2))
format(H(L("A"), L("B"), L("C"), hs=1))
format(H(L("A"), L("B"), L("C"), hs=0))
format(V(L("A"), L("B"), L("C"), vs=2))
format(V(L("A"), L("B"), L("C"), vs=1))
format(V(L("A"), L("B"), L("C"), vs=0))
format(H(L("A"), V(L("B"), L("C"))))
format(H(L("A"), I(L("B")), L("C")))
format(H(L("A"), V(L("B"), H(L("C"), L("D")))))
```

The "soft" constraints change their behavior based on available horizontal room:
```rascal-shell,continue
format(HV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..10]]));
format(HV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..20]]));
format(HV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..40]]));
format(HV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..80]]));
format(HV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..100]]));
format(HOV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..10]]));
format(HOV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..20]]));
format(HOV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..30]]));
```

By cleverly combining constraints, a specifically desired behavior is easy to achieve:
```rascal-shell,continue
format(H(L("if"), H(L("("), L("true"), L(")"), hs=0), HOV(L("doSomething"))))
format(H(L("if"), H(L("("), L("true"), L(")"), hs=0), HOV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..30]])))
format(H(L("if"), H(L("("), L("true"), L(")"), hs=0), HV([L("W<i>") | i <- [0..30]])))
```
}[0m
[3m[2m@pitfalls{
* Box2text does not have highlighting features anymore; you can use ((util::Highlight)) for this instead.
}[0m
[1mmodule[0m lang::box::util::Box2Text

[1mimport[0m util::Math;
[1mimport[0m List;
[1mimport[0m String;
[1mimport[0m lang::box::\syntax::Box;
[1mimport[0m IO;

[3m[2m@synopsis{formatting options for ((Box2Text))}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
    * `maxWidth` is the constraint that makes HV and HOV boxes switch to vertical mode (origin: ((Box2Text))
    * `wrapAfter` is the lowerbound that makes HV and HOV stay horizontal (origin ((Box2Text)))
    * `tabSize` is the default indentation used when an `I` box does not have an explicit `is` parameter (origin: ((util::LanguageServer)))
    * `insertSpaces`, when set to true it prefers spaces over tabs, when set to false we use tabs for indentation (see `tabSize`)
    * `trimTrailingWhitespace` when `true` the formatter can not leave spaces or tabs after the last non-whitespace character,
    when false it does not matter. (origin: ((util::LanguageServer)))
    * `insertFinalNewline`,  insert a newline character at the end of the file if one does not exist. (origin: ((util::LanguageServer)))
    * `trimFinalNewlines`, trim all newlines after the final newline at the end of the file. (origin: ((util::LanguageServer))

Note that there may be more FormattingOptions due to other elements of a formatting pipeline, such as ((layoutDiff)).
}[0m
[1mdata[0m FormattingOptions ([1mint[0m maxWidth = 80,
                        [1mint[0m wrapAfter = 70,
                        [1mint[0m tabSize = 4,
                        [1mbool[0m insertSpaces = [1mtrue[0m,
                        [1mbool[0m trimTrailingWhitespace = [1mtrue[0m,
                        [1mbool[0m insertFinalNewline = [1mtrue[0m,
                        [1mbool[0m trimFinalNewlines = [1mtrue[0m) = formattingOptions();

[3m[2m@synopsis{Specialized alignments for the final column to implement `trimTrailingWhitespace`}[0m
[1mprivate[0m [1mdata[0m Alignment
    = fl()
    | fc()
    ;

[3m[2m@synopsis{Converts boxes into a string by finding an "optimal" two-dimensional layout}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
* This algorithm never changes the left-to-right order of the Boxes constituents, such that
syntactical correctness is maintained
* This algorithm tries to never over-run the `maxWidth` parameter, but if it must to maintain 
text order, and the specified nesting of boxes, it will anyway. For example, if a table column doesn't
fit it will still be printed. We say `maxWidth` is a _soft_ constraint.
* Separator options like `i`, `h` and `v` options are _hard_ constraints, they may lead to overriding `maxWidth`.
* H, V and I boxes represent hard constraints too.
* HV and HOV are the soft constraints that allow for better solutions, so use them where you can to allow for 
flexible layout that can handle deeply nested expressions and statements.
}[0m
[1mpublic[0m
[1mstr[0m format(Box b, FormattingOptions opts = formattingOptions())
    = finalNewlineOptions(
          "<[1mfor[0m (line <- box2text(b, opts = opts)) {><line>
          '<}>",
          opts.insertFinalNewline,
          opts.trimFinalNewlines
      );

[1mprivate[0m
[1mstr[0m finalNewlineOptions(
    [1mstr[0m lines, [1mbool[0m insertFinalNewline, [1mbool[0m trimFinalNewlines
) {
    [1mif[0m (!insertFinalNewline) {
        lines = lines[..[1m-[0m1];
        
        [1mif[0m (trimFinalNewlines, /^<prefix:.*>\s+$/ := lines) {
            lines = prefix;
        }
    }
    [1melse[0m
        [1mif[0m (trimFinalNewlines, /^<prefix:.*>\s*$/ := lines) {
            lines = "<prefix>\n";
        }
    [1mreturn[0m lines;
}

[3m[2m@synopsis{Box2text uses list[str] as intermediate representation of the output during formatting}[0m
[3m[2m@benefits{
* Helps with fast concatenation
* Allows for measuring (max) width and height of intermediate results very quickly
}[0m
[3m[2m@pitfalls{
* Because of this representation, box2text does not recognize that unprintable characters have width 0. So,
ANSI escape codes, and characters like \r and \n in `L` boxes _will break_ the accuracy of the algorithm.
}[0m
[1malias[0m Text = [1mlist[0m[[1mstr[0m];

[3m[2m@synopsis{Converts boxes into list of lines (Unicode)}[0m
[1mpublic[0m
Text box2text(Box b, FormattingOptions opts = formattingOptions())
    = box2data(
          b,
          options(
              maxWidth = opts.maxWidth,
              wrapAfter = opts.wrapAfter,
              is = opts.tabSize,
              trimTrailingWhitespace = opts.trimTrailingWhitespace,
              insertSpaces = opts.insertSpaces
          )
      );

[3m[2m////////// private functions below implement the intermediate data-structures[0m
[3m[2m////////// and the constraint solver[0m
[3m[2m@synopsis{Configuration options for a single formatting run.}[0m
[3m[2m@description{
This is used during the algorithm, not for external usage.

* `hs` is the current separation between every horizontal element in H, HV and HOV boxes
* `vs` is the current separation between vertical elements in V, HV and HOV boxes
* `is` is the default (additional) indentation for indented boxes
* `maxWidth` is the number of columns (characters) of a single line on screen or on paper
* `wrapAfter` is the threshold criterion for line fullness, to go to the next line in a HV box and to switching
between horizontal and vertical for HOV boxes.
}[0m
[1mprivate[0m [1mdata[0m Options
    = options(
          [1mint[0m hs = 1,
          [1mint[0m vs = 0,
          [1mint[0m is = 4,
          [1mint[0m maxWidth = 80,
          [1mint[0m wrapAfter = 70,
          [1mbool[0m trimTrailingWhitespace = [1mtrue[0m,
          [1mbool[0m insertSpaces = [1mtrue[0m);

[3m[2m@synopsis{Quickly splice in any nested U boxes, and empty H, V, HV, I or HOV boxes}[0m
[1mlist[0m[Box] u([1mlist[0m[Box] boxes) {
    [1mreturn[0m
        [*((U_([1mlist[0m[Box] nested) := b) ? u(nested) : [b]) | b <- boxes, !isDegenerate(b)];
}

[3m[2m@synopsis{Empty H, V, HOV, HV, I boxes should not lead to accidental extra separators in their context}[0m
[1mprivate[0m [1mbool[0m isDegenerate(Box b) = b [1mhas[0m boxes && b.boxes == [];

[3m[2m@synopsis{simple vertical concatenation (every list element is a line)}[0m
[1mprivate[0m Text vv(Text a, Text b) = [*a, *b];

[3m[2m@synopsis{Create a string of spaces just as wide as the parameter a}[0m
[1mprivate[0m [1mstr[0m blank([1mstr[0m a, Options opts) = hskip(size(a), opts)[0];

[3m[2m@synopsis{Computes a white line with the length of the last line of a}[0m
Text wd([], Options _) = [];
Text wd([*_, [1mstr[0m x], Options opts) = [blank(x, opts)];

[3m[2m@synopsis{Computes the maximum width of text t}[0m
[1mprivate[0m [1mint[0m twidth([]) = 0;
[1mprivate[0m [1mdefault[0m [1mint[0m twidth(Text t) = max([size(line) | line <- t]);

[3m[2m@synopsis{Computes the length of the last line of t}[0m
[1mprivate[0m [1mint[0m hwidth([]) = 0;
[1mprivate[0m [1mint[0m hwidth([*_, [1mstr[0m last]) = size(last);

[3m[2m@synopsis{Prepends str a before text b, all lines of b will be shifted}[0m
[1mprivate[0m Text bar([1mstr[0m a, [], Options _) = [a];
[1mprivate[0m
Text bar([1mstr[0m a, [[1mstr[0m bh, *[1mstr[0m bt], Options opts)
    = vv(["<a><bh>"], prepend(blank(a, opts), bt));

[3m[2m@synopsis{Produce text consisting of a white line of length  n}[0m
Text hskip([1mint[0m n, Options opts)
    = opts.insertSpaces
          ? [right("", n)]
          : ["<[1mfor[0m (_ <- [0..n / opts.is]) {>\t<}><[1mfor[0m (_ <- [0..n % opts.is]) {> <}>"];

[3m[2m@synopsis{Produces text consisting of n white lines at length 0}[0m
[1mprivate[0m Text vskip([1mint[0m n) = ["" | _ <- [0..n]];

[3m[2m@synopsis{Prepend Every line in b with `a`}[0m
[1mprivate[0m Text prepend([1mstr[0m a, Text b) = ["<a><line>" | line <- b];

[3m[2m@synopsis{Implements horizontal concatenation, also for multiple lines}[0m
[1mprivate[0m Text hh([], Text b, Options _) = b;
[1mprivate[0m Text hh(Text a, [], Options _) = a;
[1mprivate[0m Text hh([a], Text b, Options opts) = bar(a, b, opts);

[1mprivate[0m
[1mdefault[0m Text hh(Text a, Text b, Options opts)
    = vv(a[0..[1m-[0m1], bar(a[[1m-[0m1], b, opts));

[3m[2m@synopsis{Horizontal concatenation, but if the left text is empty return nothing.}[0m
